03899nmm a2200589Ia 9781479883844DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814798838447 a10.18574/nyu/9781479883844.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)547604  a(OCoLC)961826081  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPK6412.I73bM66 2016 7aLCO0120002bisacsh04a891/.550935855054222300aMoments of Silence :bAuthenticity in the Cultural Expressions of the Iran-Iraq War, 1980-1988 /ced. by Arta Khakpour, Shouleh Vatanabadi, Mohammad Mehdi Khorrami. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExplores how writers, filmmakers and artists have attempted to reckon with the legacy of a devastating warThe Iran-Iraq War was the longest conventional war of the 20th century. The memory of it may have faded in the wake of more recent wars in the region, but the harrowing facts remain: over one million soldiers and civilians dead, millions more permanently displaced and disabled, and an entire generation marked by prosthetic implants and teenage martyrdom. These same facts have been instrumentalized by agendas both foreign and domestic, but also aestheticized, defamiliarized, readdressed and reconciled by artists, writers, and filmmakers across an array of identities: linguistic (Arabic, Persian, Kurdish), religious (Shiite, Sunni, atheist), and political (Iranian, Iraqi, internationalist). Official discourses have unsurprisingly tried to dominate the process of production and distribution of war narratives. In doing so, they have ignored and silenced other voices. Centering on novels, films, memoirs, and poster art that gave aesthetic expression to the Iran-Iraq War, the essays gathered in this volume present multiple perspectives on the war’s most complex and underrepresented narratives. These scholars do not naively claim to represent an authenticity lacking in official discourses of the war, but rather, they call into question the notion of authenticity itself. Finding, deciding upon, and creating a language that can convey any sort of truth at all—collective, national, or private—is the major preoccupation of the texts and critiques in this diverse collection.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aIran-Iraq War, 1980-1988xLiterature and the war. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh1 aKhakpour, Arta, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKhorrami, Mohammad Mehdi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVatanabadi, Shouleh, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479883844.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479883844423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479883844/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles